VALUES
(19, 135, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Blessed be the Lord out of Zion', 0, 31, 'connection', 'Zion in Scripture', 'The phrase ''out of Zion'' connects to Hebrews 12:22, where the author refers to ''Mount Zion, the city of the living God.'' This connection emphasizes Zion as a central place of divine presence and worship, reinforcing the idea that God''s blessings and actions flow from this sacred site, linking it to the New Testament understanding of the Church as the spiritual Zion.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 12:22", "description": "References the significance of Zion in the New Covenant context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 135, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'which dwelleth at Jerusalem', 33, 60, 'theology', 'God''s Dwelling Place', 'This phrase indicates God''s choice to dwell among His people in Jerusalem, symbolizing His covenant relationship with Israel. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader theological theme of God desiring to be with His people, seen in both the Old and New Testaments, culminating in the incarnation of Christ (John 1:14).', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of God''s dwelling among His people."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 135, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Praise ye the Lord.', 62, 81, 'question', 'Call to Praise', 'What does it mean to genuinely praise the Lord in our daily lives? Considering this command, how can we express our gratitude and honor toward God through actions and words, reflecting a heart aligned with His will?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'O give thanks unto the Lord;', 0, 28, 'connection', 'Call to Worship', 'This phrase resonates with other exhortations to give thanks, such as 1 Chronicles 16:34, which also emphasizes God''s goodness and mercy. This connection highlights a recurring theme throughout the Scriptures where gratitude is a vital response to God''s character and deeds, encouraging believers to cultivate a thankful heart.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Chronicles 16:34", "description": "A call to give thanks for God''s enduring mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'for he is good:', 29, 44, 'theology', 'Nature of God''s Goodness', 'Many scholars believe that God''s goodness is fundamental to His nature, reflecting His righteousness and faithfulness. This passage suggests that recognizing God''s goodness is essential for understanding His mercy, as seen in the theological framework of God''s covenant relationship with His people. This understanding invites believers to trust in God''s character.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 45, 77, 'greek', 'Mercy in the Original Language', 'חֶסֶד (chesed, H2617) - lovingkindness, steadfast love. This Hebrew term encapsulates God''s enduring commitment to His people, reflecting His covenant faithfulness. The repeated affirmation of His mercy enduring forever serves as a reminder of the unbreakable bond between God and His creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2617", "description": "Strong''s definition of ''chesed.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'O give thanks unto the Lord;', 0, 28, 'question', 'Personal Reflection on Gratitude', 'In what ways do you actively express gratitude to the Lord in your daily life? How does acknowledging His goodness and mercy shape your perspective during challenging times?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'God of gods', 23, 34, 'connection', 'Divine Supremacy', 'This phrase ''God of gods'' emphasizes the supremacy of the Lord over all other deities. It parallels Deuteronomy 10:17, which states, ''For the Lord your God is God of gods and Lord of lords.'' This connection highlights the monotheistic belief central to Israelite faith and serves as a reminder of God''s unparalleled authority and sovereignty.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 10:17", "description": "Affirms God''s supremacy over all other gods."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'O give thanks', 0, 13, 'theology', 'Call to Gratitude', 'The repeated call to ''give thanks'' throughout this psalm reflects the theological concept of gratitude as a response to God''s benevolence. Many scholars believe that expressing thanks cultivates a deeper relationship with God and reminds believers of His continuous mercy and provision in their lives. This teaching aligns with 1 Thessalonians 5:18, which encourages believers to give thanks in all circumstances.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Thessalonians 5:18", "description": "Encourages gratitude in all circumstances."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 36, 67, 'question', 'Nature of God''s Mercy', 'What does it mean for God''s mercy to endure forever? In what ways can we experience and reflect this eternal mercy in our daily lives? Reflecting on this phrase invites a deeper understanding of God''s unchanging nature and encourages us to embody mercy in our interactions with others.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'God of gods', 23, 34, 'greek', 'Understanding ''God''', 'אֱלֹהִים (elohim, H430) - God, deities. This term denotes not only the singular God of Israel but also the plural form that acknowledges His supremacy over all other divine beings. The use of ''elohim'' in this context emphasizes the uniqueness and sovereignty of the God of Israel.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H430", "description": "Identifies the term for God in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'O give thanks to the Lord of lords: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 68, 'connection', 'Divine Sovereignty', 'The phrase ''Lord of lords'' connects to Deuteronomy 10:17, which describes God as the supreme ruler over all divine beings. This emphasizes His unmatched authority and power, reinforcing the call to thanksgiving as an acknowledgment of His ultimate sovereignty. Additionally, Revelation 17:14 refers to Christ as ''Lord of lords,'' illustrating the continuity of this title through both the Old and New Testaments.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 10:17", "description": "Highlights God''s supremacy over all gods."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Revelation 17:14", "description": "Shows Christ''s authority as ''Lord of lords.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'Lord of lords', 21, 34, 'greek', 'Transcendent Title', 'κύριος (kyrios, G2962) - lord, master, owner. This term signifies authority and divinity, indicating God''s supremacy not only over earthly rulers but also over spiritual entities. Understanding this term deepens appreciation for God''s unparalleled position in both heaven and earth.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2962", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term for lord."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 36, 68, 'theology', 'Nature of God''s Mercy', 'This verse affirms a foundational Christian belief in the eternal nature of God''s mercy. Many scholars believe that His mercy is not only everlasting but also a key aspect of His character, providing hope and assurance to believers. The doctrine of God''s mercy suggests that His love and compassion are unchanging and always available to those who seek Him.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the nature of God''s mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'give thanks', 2, 13, 'question', 'Understanding Gratitude', 'What does it mean to ''give thanks'' to the ''Lord of lords'' in your daily life? How can acknowledging His mercy influence your perspective and actions, especially in challenging circumstances? Reflecting on this may lead to a deeper understanding of the significance of gratitude in your spiritual journey.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'To him who alone doeth great wonders', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Divine Wonders Across Scripture', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in Exodus 15:11, which proclaims, ''Who is like you, O Lord, among the gods? Who is like you, majestic in holiness, awesome in glorious deeds, doing wonders?'' Both verses emphasize God''s unparalleled power and uniqueness. The connection underscores the theme of God''s greatness in performing miraculous acts, inviting believers to acknowledge His sovereignty.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 15:11", "description": "A declaration of God''s unique power and miraculous deeds."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'doeth great wonders', 17, 36, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Wonders''', 'θαυμάσια (thaumasia, G2296) - wonders, miracles. This term captures the essence of extraordinary acts that provoke awe and reverence. In this context, it highlights God''s capability to perform acts beyond human comprehension, affirming His divine nature and the call for gratitude for His merciful actions.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2296", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term for wonders."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 38, 69, 'theology', 'Theological Significance of Mercy', 'This passage suggests a profound theological truth about God''s enduring mercy. Many scholars believe that the repetitive phrase ''for his mercy endureth for ever'' serves to remind believers of God''s unchanging character, highlighting His steadfast love and faithfulness. This foundational aspect of God''s nature encourages believers to trust in His promises and grace throughout their lives.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the nature of God''s mercy throughout Scripture."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'To him who alone doeth great wonders', 0, 36, 'question', 'Reflecting on Divine Uniqueness', 'What does it mean to acknowledge God as ''alone'' in performing great wonders? How does recognizing His sole authority in miraculous acts influence your understanding of His role in your life and the world around you?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'To him that by wisdom made the heavens: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 72, 'connection', 'Creation''s Wisdom', 'This verse connects to Proverbs 3:19, which states, ''The Lord by wisdom founded the earth; by understanding He established the heavens.'' Both verses emphasize God''s wisdom in creation, highlighting that the universe''s intricate design is a testament to His character. Understanding this connection deepens our appreciation for God''s creative power and the intentionality behind it.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 3:19", "description": "Shows the link between wisdom and creation"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'by wisdom', 12, 21, 'greek', 'Wisdom in Creation', 'σοφία (sophia, G4678) - wisdom, insight, skill. This term signifies not just intellectual knowledge but also practical applied knowledge. Here, it denotes the divine wisdom that orchestrated the creation of the heavens, suggesting that the universe operates under a divine order and purpose.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4678", "description": "Indicates the depth of the word ''wisdom''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'made the heavens', 22, 38, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Creation', 'This phrase underscores the doctrine of creation ex nihilo, meaning creation ''out of nothing.'' Many scholars believe this reflects God''s sovereign authority over the universe, affirming that nothing exists outside of His will. This understanding shapes our view of God as not just a creator, but as the ultimate source of all being and existence.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "John Calvin''s ''Institutes of the Christian Religion''", "description": "Discusses the doctrine of creation"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 40, 72, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Mercy', 'What does it mean for God''s mercy to endure forever in the context of creation? How does this eternal aspect of His mercy shape your understanding of the world around you and His ongoing relationship with creation? Reflecting on this can deepen your appreciation for the constancy of God''s love and care.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'stretched out the earth above the waters', 12, 52, 'connection', 'Creation Imagery', 'This phrase directly resonates with Genesis 1:9, where God commands the waters to be gathered, allowing dry land to appear. The imagery of God stretching out the earth evokes His sovereignty in creation and reinforces His power over chaos. Connecting these verses emphasizes the consistent theme of God''s creative authority and His enduring mercy in establishing the world we inhabit.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:9", "description": "God''s command in creation, highlighting His authority over waters."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 54, 85, 'theology', 'God''s Eternal Mercy', 'The repetition of ''for his mercy endureth for ever'' throughout Psalm 136 underscores a central theme of God''s character: His steadfast love and mercy. Many scholars believe this reflects the covenantal nature of God''s relationship with His people, illustrating that His mercy is not fleeting but an everlasting attribute, foundational to the faithfulness seen in His actions throughout history.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of God''s enduring mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'stretched out the earth above the waters', 12, 52, 'greek', 'Hebrew Word Analysis', 'רָחַב (rachav, H7337) - to be wide or spacious. This term conveys the idea of God expanding or stretching out the earth, illustrating His creative power and intentional design in separating land from water. The use of this word enriches our understanding of God''s authority in creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7337", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'stretched out the earth above the waters', 12, 52, 'question', 'Understanding Creation''s Order', 'What does it mean for God to ''stretch out the earth above the waters''? How does this image shape our understanding of His power and the order within creation? Reflecting on this can deepen our appreciation of God''s intentionality and care in the physical world.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'To him that made great lights:', 0, 30, 'connection', 'Creation Connection', 'This phrase echoes the creation account in Genesis 1:16, where God creates the sun, moon, and stars as ''great lights'' to govern day and night. The connection underscores God''s sovereignty over creation, emphasizing His role as the ultimate creator. It reinforces the idea that these celestial bodies are not just physical entities, but also manifestations of God''s creative power and purpose.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:16", "description": "God''s creation of the sun and moon"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 31, 63, 'theology', 'Enduring Mercy', 'The repeated phrase ''for his mercy endureth for ever'' emphasizes the theological concept of God''s everlasting mercy. Many scholars believe this reflects the covenantal nature of God''s relationship with His people, suggesting that His mercy is unchanging and eternal, serving as a foundation for hope and trust in His promises throughout Scripture.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the nature of God''s mercy"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'To him that made great lights:', 0, 30, 'question', 'Reflecting on Creation', 'What does it mean for you personally to acknowledge God as the creator of the ''great lights''? How does this understanding influence your perception of His authority over your life and the world around you?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'The sun to rule by day: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 56, 'connection', 'Creation and Authority', 'This verse connects with Genesis 1:16, where God creates the sun to govern the day. It emphasizes God''s authority over creation and His provision of light, symbolizing His guidance and mercy. The recurring phrase ''for his mercy endureth for ever'' indicates that God''s creation is not only functional but also a reflection of His enduring mercy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:16", "description": "Describes God''s creation of the sun and moon."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'The sun to rule by day:', 0, 23, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''rule''', 'Greek word ''κράτος'' (kratos, G2904) - power, dominion. While this verse is in Hebrew, the Greek translation reveals that the sun''s ''ruling'' signifies a form of dominion and authority that God has established in creation. This underscores the idea that God''s order is purposeful and reflects His sovereignty.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2904", "description": "Strong''s number for ''kratos''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 24, 56, 'theology', 'God''s Eternal Mercy', 'This phrase suggests a theological affirmation of God''s unchanging nature and His covenantal love towards His creation. Many scholars believe that the repetition of God''s mercy throughout this Psalm emphasizes His faithfulness and the assurance that His love is consistent, regardless of human circumstances or failures.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the nature of God''s mercy as everlasting."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'The sun to rule by day:', 0, 23, 'question', 'Reflection on Divine Order', 'What does it mean for you personally to recognize the sun as a symbol of God''s rule during the day? How might this understanding influence your perspective on God''s presence and authority in your daily life?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'The moon and stars to rule by night: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 69, 'connection', 'Creation and Divine Order', 'This verse echoes Genesis 1:16, where God creates the sun, moon, and stars to govern the day and night. Both passages emphasize God''s sovereignty in creation and the enduring nature of His mercy. The repeated phrase ''for his mercy endureth for ever'' highlights that God''s creative authority is not only functional but also rooted in His loving character, suggesting that even the celestial bodies are a testament to His grace.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:16", "description": "God creating the sun, moon, and stars"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'The moon and stars to rule by night: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 69, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty and Mercy', 'This passage suggests that God''s creation is imbued with purpose and reflects His enduring mercy. Many scholars believe that the consistent return of the moon and stars each night serves as a reminder of God''s faithfulness and care for His creation. This reinforces the theological understanding that God''s mercy is a foundational attribute, sustaining the universe and His people throughout time.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'The moon and stars to rule by night: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 69, 'question', 'Reflection on God''s Creation', 'How does recognizing the moon and stars as symbols of God''s mercy influence your understanding of His creation? In what ways can you see the enduring nature of His mercy reflected in the world around you?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'The moon and stars to rule by night: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 69, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Mercy''', 'חֶסֶד (chesed, H2617) - steadfast love, kindness. This Hebrew term conveys a depth of loyalty and love that God extends to His creation, emphasizing that His mercy is not just a feeling but an active commitment to His people. The use of this term in the context of the verse underscores the perpetual nature of God''s mercy as a governing force in the world.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2617", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for mercy"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'To him that smote Egypt in their firstborn: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 76, 'connection', 'Passover Reference', 'This verse connects directly to Exodus 12:29-30, where God strikes down the firstborn of Egypt. This act is pivotal in the narrative of Israel''s deliverance, emphasizing God''s judgment against oppression and His protective mercy for His people. The repeated phrase ''for his mercy endureth for ever'' serves as a refrain that highlights God''s enduring love amidst His acts of judgment.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 12:29-30", "description": "The account of the death of the firstborn in Egypt."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'smote Egypt in their firstborn', 12, 42, 'theology', 'Judgment and Salvation', 'The act of God smiting Egypt''s firstborn signifies divine judgment but also sets the stage for Israel''s salvation. Many scholars believe this reflects a broader theological theme where judgment is often intertwined with mercy, showcasing God''s commitment to deliverance. This duality invites believers to recognize the seriousness of sin while celebrating God''s redemptive work.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the themes of judgment and mercy in God''s actions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 44, 76, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Mercy', 'What does it mean for God''s mercy to endure forever, especially in the context of judgment? How does this eternal aspect of mercy inform your understanding of God''s character and His actions throughout history?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'To him that smote Egypt in their firstborn', 0, 42, 'greek', 'Hebrew Insight', 'מַכָּה (makah, H5221) - strike, smite. This term emphasizes not just a physical blow but a decisive action by God against injustice. Understanding this word provides depth to the notion of divine retribution in the context of liberation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5221", "description": "Hebrew word for ''smote'' used in this context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'And brought out Israel from among them: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 72, 'connection', 'Exodus Connection', 'This verse echoes the pivotal event of the Exodus, where God delivered Israel from Egyptian bondage (Exodus 12:51). The phrase highlights God''s active role in salvation history, emphasizing His enduring mercy. Additionally, Deuteronomy 7:8 reiterates that it was God''s love and faithfulness that led to Israel''s deliverance, reinforcing the theme of divine mercy throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 12:51", "description": "God''s deliverance of Israel from Egypt."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 7:8", "description": "God''s love and faithfulness in delivering Israel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'brought out Israel from among them', 4, 38, 'theology', 'Salvation Theme', 'This passage reflects a central theme in biblical theology: God''s initiative in salvation. Many scholars believe this demonstrates God''s sovereignty and compassion, showcasing that He actively intervenes in human affairs to rescue His people. This concept aligns with the New Testament understanding of salvation through Christ, where God continues to ''bring out'' believers from spiritual bondage.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 40, 72, 'greek', 'Mercy in Greek', 'חֶסֶד (chesed, H2617) - steadfast love, mercy. This Hebrew term represents God''s unwavering commitment to His covenant people, emphasizing that His mercy is not fleeting but eternal. This enduring quality of God''s mercy reassures believers of His constant presence and faithfulness throughout generations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2617", "description": "Strong''s number for ''chesed''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'brought out Israel from among them', 4, 38, 'question', 'Reflection on Deliverance', 'What does it mean for you personally to be ''brought out'' from the challenges or sins that bind you? How does recognizing God''s enduring mercy shape your understanding of your own deliverance?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'With a strong hand, and with a stretched out arm:', 0, 49, 'connection', 'Divine Power in Exodus', 'This phrase echoes God''s deliverance of Israel from Egypt, particularly in Exodus 6:1, where He states, ''Now you will see what I will do to Pharaoh; for with a strong hand he will let them go, and with a strong hand he will drive them out of his land.'' This connection emphasizes God''s might in salvation history, showcasing His ability to intervene powerfully on behalf of His people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 6:1", "description": "God''s promise of deliverance reinforced"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 50, 82, 'theology', 'God''s Everlasting Mercy', 'This refrain emphasizes the theological concept of God''s steadfast love and mercy (chesed in Hebrew). Many scholars believe this repetition serves to remind believers of God''s unchanging nature and His covenant faithfulness, which assures that His mercy is not contingent on circumstances but is an eternal aspect of His character.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'With a strong hand, and with a stretched out arm:', 0, 49, 'greek', 'Hebrew Terms of Strength', 'יָד (yad, H3027) - hand; זְרוֹעַ (zeroa, H2220) - arm. These terms denote power and might, illustrating God''s active involvement in the history of Israel. The usage in this context signifies not just physical strength but also divine authority in delivering His people from bondage.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3027", "description": "Strong''s number for ''hand''"}, {"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2220", "description": "Strong''s number for ''arm''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 50, 82, 'question', 'Reflection on God''s Mercy', 'What does it mean for you personally that God''s mercy ''endureth for ever''? How does this truth influence your understanding of forgiveness and redemption in your life today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');